:: Next Scenario → Scenario 10 - Cerebral Palsy {"position":"1500,2100","size":"100,100"}
- Scenario 10 - Cerebral Palsy
A student with **cerebral palsy** is struggling to write with a traditional pencil in class.

What do you do?


Option 1.
[[Suggest they try harder and practice writing more.]]  
<img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/3791136/pexels-photo-3791136.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" 
alt="A student with cerebral palsy being told to practice writing more despite physical difficulties, leading to frustration." width="600">

Option 2.
[[Provide assistive tools like a speech-to-text device or a grip-friendly stylus.]]  
<img src="https://media.istockphoto.com/id/861092546/photo/speech-recognition-concept-hands-free-communication-machine-translation.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=8JWp4o2-02DHQop0Rk9li7fFkcnqSH6GA2L5ORbRw6o=" 
alt="An assistive speech-to-text device in use, allowing a person with fine motor impairments to communicate more effectively." width="600">



:: Next Scenario → Scenario 2 - Hearing Impairment {"position":"1500,500","size":"100,100"}
- Scenario 2 - Hearing Impairment
A guest who is **Deaf** asks if they can get **live captions** during a conference presentation.

What do you do?


Option 1.
[[Arrange for live captions and sign language interpretation.]]  
<img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/7516283/pexels-photo-7516283.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1260&h=750&dpr=2" 
alt="An accessible conference with live captions on a screen and a sign language interpreter, ensuring Deaf individuals can understand the presentation." width="600">

Option 2.
[[Tell them to sit closer to the speaker.]]  
<img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/8761518/pexels-photo-8761518.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" 
alt="A person sitting closer to the speaker, but still unable to understand the presentation due to their hearing impairment." width="600">




:: Next Scenario → Scenario 3 - Mobility Impairment {"position":"1500,700","size":"100,100"}
- Scenario 3 - Mobility Impairment
Your office space has **desks and meeting rooms up a short flight of stairs**. 

What do you do?


Option 1.
[[Approve the design – stairs are short, so it should be fine.]]  
<img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/9400756/pexels-photo-9400756.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1260&h=750&dpr=2" 
alt="A workplace with stairs but no wheelchair access, preventing mobility-impaired individuals from entering." width="600">

Option 2.
[[Ensure there’s a ramp and elevator access.]]  
<img src="https://plus.unsplash.com/premium_photo-1661377004977-ced9bdc93926?w=700&auto=format&fit=crop&q=60&ixlib=rb-4.0.3&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxzZWFyY2h8MXx8V2hlZWxjaGFpciUyMG1hdHVyZSUyMHdvbWFuJTIwbGVhdmluZyUyMGVsZXZhdG9yfGVufDB8fDB8fHww" 
alt="A wheelchair user accessing an office building via a ramp and elevator, ensuring inclusivity for people with mobility impairments." width="600">



:: Next Scenario → Scenario 4 - Speech Impairment {"position":"1500,900","size":"100,100"}
- Scenario 4 - Speech Impairment
A customer using a **speech-generating device** is struggling to communicate with a cashier.

What should you do?


Option 1.
[[Tell the customer to type faster so the cashier can move on.]]  
<img src="https://media.istockphoto.com/id/688787498/photo/group-of-people-screaming-in-megaphones-at-scared-guy.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=_I45tbKQmS4hl3Sz-_6VJnbh2pD9B44YRNEbH5Wie2c=" 
alt="An impatient and rushed interaction, making communication more difficult for the customer." width="600">

Option 2.
[[Encourage the cashier to be patient and allow the customer time to communicate.]]  
<img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/8015694/pexels-photo-8015694.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1260&h=750&dpr=2" 
alt="A kind and patient interaction where a cashier attentively listens to a customer using a speech-generating device." width="600">



:: Next Scenario → Scenario 5 - Prosthetic Limb Use {"position":"1500,1100","size":"100,100"}
- Scenario 5 - Prosthetic Limb Use
A gym member with a **prosthetic leg** joins a fitness class with jumping exercises.

How do you accommodate them?


Option 1.
[[Offer alternative exercises that match their ability level.]]  
<img src="https://media.istockphoto.com/id/503665318/photo/female-physiotherapist-helping-young-man-with-prosthetic-leg.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=Xuxb4ZrUSSRseYHoj_z-PBDzzd-AC5BxAPVQb1RnoTI=" 
alt="A physiotherapist assisting a young man with a prosthetic leg, demonstrating support and accessibility in physical therapy." width="600">

Option 2.
[[Tell them to do the jumping exercises anyway.]]  
<img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/8560716/pexels-photo-8560716.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" 
alt="An individual with a prosthetic leg struggling to perform a jumping exercise that is not adapted to their abilities." width="600">




:: Next Scenario → Scenario 6 - Hand Mobility Impairment {"position":"1500,1300","size":"100,100"}
- Scenario 6 - Hand Mobility Impairment
A coworker with **limited hand mobility** is struggling to use a **touchscreen-only vending machine**.

What do you do?


Option 1.
[[Don't do anything, let them struggle.]]  
<img src="https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2016/05/28/13/04/boys-1421410_1280.jpg"alt="A helpful coworker assisting someone with limited hand mobility at a vending machine, showing support and accessibility solutions." width="600">

Option 2.
[[Help them use the machine, or find assistance, and suggest an accessible alternative.]]  
<img src="https://media.istockphoto.com/id/1225915764/photo/women-co-workers-are-at-work-break-using-coworking-office-vending-machine.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=FLemTwP10c7VJOurpm8U9x7pP4jWVl7oF-xZMdm6x98=" 
alt="A person with limited hand mobility being ignored while trying to use a vending machine, making the experience frustrating and isolating." width="600">



:: Next Scenario → Scenario 7 - Muscular Dystrophy {"position":"1500,1500","size":"100,100"}
- Scenario 7 - Muscular Dystrophy
Your school gym is installing **new weightlifting machines**. A student with **muscular dystrophy** asks if the machines can be modified.

What do you do?


Option 1.
[[Tell them the machines are standard, and they should try to use them as they are.]]  
<img src="https://media.istockphoto.com/id/1160507739/photo/tired-fitness-running-woman-sweating-exhausted.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=FkDDtXXurKxeJ2piIXUyN5zUJIikHA6QfxcBFt0u0-8=" 
alt="A person struggling with a workout because the equipment is not adapted for their condition, leading to exhaustion and frustration." width="600">

Option 2.
[[Work with the gym to add adjustable resistance levels and grips.]]  
<img src="https://media.istockphoto.com/id/1392310150/photo/young-man-helping-his-girlfriend-during-her-sports-training-in-a-health-club.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=db1uW5yKg04GawBIoAcFjHyy1TRnEd1OVAFfYaN76kY=" 
alt="A supportive gym environment where a person receives assistance and uses properly adjusted equipment, ensuring inclusivity." width="600">



:: Next Scenario → Scenario 8 - Spinal Cord Injury {"position":"1500,1700","size":"100,100"}
- Scenario 8 - Spinal Cord Injury
A coworker who **uses a wheelchair** asks if the **office temperature** can be more stable since they have trouble **regulating body heat**.

What do you do?


Option 1.
[[Adjust the office temperature and offer flexible seating.]]  
<img src="https://media.istockphoto.com/id/1084278508/photo/man-adjusting-temperature-with-thermostat-at-home.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=A0KNmYrM3gqnOiiEYrKkB555Gch34TaUwYrlZBns470=" 
alt="An employee adjusting the office thermostat to maintain a stable temperature, making the environment comfortable for coworkers with temperature regulation issues." width="600">

Option 2.
[[Tell them to bring extra layers or a fan.]]  
<img src="https://media.istockphoto.com/id/1429950972/photo/the-bills-for-this-month-are-too-high.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=8Auw-u6_Hpn5fg-CRqeBiYJP9gsmFkmHI7ZDU5PsA9Q=" 
alt="A person struggling to cope with inconsistent temperatures by using extra layers or personal fans instead of workplace accommodations." width="600">




:: Next Scenario → Scenario 9 - Chronic Pain & Fatigue {"position":"1500,1900","size":"100,100"}
- Scenario 9 - Chronic Pain & Fatigue
A public event has **limited seating**. Someone with **chronic pain** asks if they can sit down, but they **do not appear visibly disabled**.

What do you do?


Option 1.
[[Tell them seating is only for people with 'real' disabilities.]]  
<img src="https://media.istockphoto.com/id/874448924/photo/young-teenager-girl-woman-standing-sadness-shadow-silhouette-iso.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=oJsPQVIB2klgLilB8atFt-vwz-Pvf87Fc3j25VgnNAY=" 
alt="A shadowed figure representing the struggle of individuals with invisible disabilities who are not immediately recognized as needing assistance." width="600">

Option 2.
[[Allow them to sit, recognizing that not all disabilities are visible.]]  
<img src="https://media.istockphoto.com/id/1482324326/photo/portrait-of-businesswoman-sitting-on-chair-in-studio-with-gray-background.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=Fprnon53GW2RahpnnDIf9YGfVMs0dfS5TB9VdQbJRy4=" 
alt="A person being denied a seat because they don’t look disabled, reinforcing the misunderstanding of invisible disabilities." width="600">


